06059nam a22008775i 9780812203639DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013947524  a(OCoLC)979753834  a97808122036397 a10.9783/97808122036392doi  a(DE-B1597)449027  a(OCoLC)794700607  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a002.091 aDane, Joseph A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOut of Sorts :bOn Typography and Print Culture /cJoseph A. Dane. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b38 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMaterial Texts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- tPART I Out of Sorts -- tChapter one. On the Continuity of Continuity: Print Culture Mythology and the Type of the Gutenberg Bible (B42) -- tChapter two. Gottfried Zedler and the Twentieth- Century History of DK Type -- tChapter three. The Voodoo Economics of Space: From Gothic to Roman -- tChapter four. The Typographical Gothic: A Cautionary Note on the Title Page to Percy’s Reliques of Ancient English Poetry -- tInterlude: At the Typographical Altar: Interlude for Randall McLeod -- tPART II Images and Texts -- tChapter five. Fists and Filiations in Early Chaucer Folios, 1532–1602 -- tChapter six. Editorial and Typographical Diplomacy in the Piers Plowman Archive -- tChapter seven. The Representation of Representation: Versions of Linear Perspective -- tChapter eight. Typographical Antiquity in Thomas Frognall Dibdin’s Typographical Antiquities -- tConclusion Print Culture Redivivus -- tNotes -- tPrincipal works cited -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe new history of the book has constituted a vibrant academic field in recent years, and theories of print culture have moved to the center of much scholarly discourse. One might think typography would be a basic element in the construction of these theories, yet if only we would pay careful attention to detail, Joseph A. Dane argues, we would find something else entirely: that a careful consideration of typography serves not as a material support to prevailing theories of print but, rather, as a recalcitrant counter-voice to them.In Out of Sorts Dane continues his examination of the ways in which the grand narratives of book history mask what we might actually learn by looking at books themselves. He considers the differences between internal and external evidence for the nature of the type used by Gutenberg and the curious disconnection between the two, and he explores how descriptions of typesetting devices from the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries have been projected back onto the fifteenth to make the earlier period not more accessible but less. In subsequent chapters, he considers topics that include the modern mythologies of so-called gothic typefaces, the presence of nontypographical elements in typographical form, and the assumptions that underlie the electronic editions of a medieval poem or the visual representation of typographical history in nineteenth-century studies of the subject.Is Dane one of the most original or most traditional of historians of print? In Out of Sorts he demonstrates that it may well be possible to be both things at once.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBibliographyvMethodologyxHistory. 0aBibliography, Critical. 0aEarly printed booksvBibliographyvMethodology. 0aEarly printed booksxBibliographyxMethodology. 0aIncunabulavBibliographyvMethodology. 0aIncunabulaxBibliographyxMethodology. 0aPrintingvHistoriography. 0aPrintin